article.headline: Oregon State 69, Gonzaga 64
article.story:
CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- First-round victories in the Women's
National Invitation Tournament are becoming the norm for Oregon
State.

Leilani Estavan had her first career double-double with 20
points and 10 assists as Oregon State defeated Gonzaga 69-64 Friday
in the first round of the WNIT, before 1,207 at Gill Coliseum.

Oregon State, hosting a WNIT first-round game for the fourth
consecutive year, advances to the second round for the third
straight year.

Ashley Burke had 17 points and Shannon Mathews added 16 points
for Gonzaga (18-12, 10-4 West Coast Conference), which made its
first postseason appearance since 1994.

"Our experience helped us," Oregon State coach Judy Spoelstra
said. "We knew their lack of experience of being in the NIT (would
help OSU). They looked a little gassed while we were making our
run."

Brina Chaney, Hollye Chapman and Shannon Howell each added 10
points for the Beavers (16-14 overall, 8-10 Pacific-10 Conference),
who play at Nebraska in the second round Monday. "I'm excited to
go back and play against them," said Howell, a junior transfer
from Nebraska. "It probably won't hit me until I get there."

Mandy Closes free throw with 3:17 to play gave the Beavers their
largest lead of the game at 59-48. Gonzaga's full-court pressure
then forced three straight OSU turnovers, sparking a 13-4 run for
the Zags.

Burkes 3-pointer with 43 seconds capped the run, cutting
Gonzaga's deficit to 63-61. But that's as close as the Zags would
get. The Beavers hit all 10 of their free-throw attempts in the
final 1:37 to seal the win. "I was proud of the way our kids
played in the last five minutes," Gonzaga coach Kelly Graves said.

"My question to them in the locker room was, 'How come we
didn't play with that same urgency the entire game?"

The Zags jumped out to an 8-0 lead and led by as much as 10
midway through the first half.

"We were just making very slow decisions at the beginning of
the game," Spoelstra said.
